# Sprint Planning and Release Timeline

**6-month delivery plan with iterative releases**

| Sprint | Weeks | Focus Area | Key Deliverables | Demo Date |
|--------|-------|------------|------------------|-----------|
| **Sprint 1-2** | 1-4 | Foundation Setup | Architecture, CI/CD, Login | Jan 29 |
| **Sprint 3-4** | 5-8 | Account Management | Profile, Settings, Password Reset | Feb 26 |
| **Sprint 5-6** | 9-12 | Service Requests | View/Submit Requests, Status Tracking | Mar 26 |
| **Sprint 7-8** | 13-16 | Billing Integration | View Bills, Payment Processing | Apr 23 |
| **Sprint 9-10** | 17-20 | Support Features | Chat, FAQ, Knowledge Base | May 21 |
| **Sprint 11-12** | 21-24 | Polish & Launch | Performance, Security, Go-Live | {{go_live_date}} |

**Release Strategy: Beta launch after Sprint 10, production launch Sprint 12**

@notes:
- Sprint planning provides predictable delivery
- Each sprint builds on previous functionality
- Demo dates create accountability and feedback
- Beta launch enables real user testing

---

# Technology Standards and Guidelines

**Ensuring code quality and consistency**

::: success
**Development Standards:**
- **Code Style:** ESLint + Prettier for consistent formatting
- **Testing:** 80% code coverage minimum with Jest/React Testing Library
- **Documentation:** JSDoc for API documentation, README for setup
- **Performance:** Lighthouse score >90 for Core Web Vitals
- **Security:** OWASP Top 10 compliance, dependency scanning
- **Accessibility:** WCAG 2.1 AA compliance validation
:::

**Code Quality Gates:**
- Automated testing must pass before merge
- Code review required from senior team member
- Security scan and dependency check on every build
- Performance testing on staging environment

@notes:
- Standards ensure maintainable, quality code
- Automated enforcement reduces manual oversight
- Performance and security built into process
- Code quality gates prevent technical debt

---

